   ('Gunpowder technology contributed to the rise of the Ottoman, Safavid, and Mughal empires primarily by',
    ['Enabling their navies to dominate the Indian Ocean', 'Allowing them to breach fortified cities and suppress cavalry-based opposition', 'Reducing the cost of maintaining large standing armies', 'Providing the technology for early industrialization']),
   ('The Mughal emperor Aurangzeb\'s reimposition of the jizya tax differed from Akbar\'s policies in that it',
    ['Increased Mughal revenues while alienating non-Muslim communities essential to imperial stability', 'Had no significant effect on the empire\'s religious communities', 'Was popular with Rajput nobles who supported it', 'Reduced taxes overall while targeting Muslims specifically']),
   ('Empires in the 1450–1750 period used monumental architecture primarily to',
    ['House armies in urban centers', 'Project imperial legitimacy and power to subjects and foreign visitors', 'Provide economic stimulus through construction employment', 'Store tribute goods from conquered peoples']),
